        "last_activity_date": 1542022336,
        "creation_date": 1542020095,
        "answer_count": 2,
        "title": "In java if &quot;char c = &#39;a&#39; &quot; why does &quot;c = c + 1&quot; not compile?",
        "body": "<p>I tried to compile the following code:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public static void main(String[] args){\n    for (char c = 'a'; c &lt;='z'; c = c + 1) {\n        System.out.println(c);\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>When I try to compile, it throws: <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Error:(5, 41) java: incompatible types: possible lossy conversion from\n  int to char<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The thing is, it does work if I write <code>c = (char)(c + 1)<\/code>, <code>c += 1<\/code> or <code>c++<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>I checked and the compiler throws a similar error when I try <code>char c = Character.MAX_VALUE + 1;<\/code> but I see no way that the value of 'c' can pass 'char' type maximum in the original function.<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 53260641,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "casting",
            "compiler-errors",
            "char",
            "primitive-types"
        ],
        "score": 3,
        "accepted_answer_id": 53260669,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 2560,
        "last_edit_date": 1542020490
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/44c841338e1646af9a977f1fa0e23948?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 162699,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3788176,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3788176/andy-turner",
                "reputation": 141045,
                "display_name": "Andy Turner",
                "accept_rate": 54
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 12,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1542020685,
            "creation_date": 1542020181,
            "body": "<p><code>c + 1<\/code> is an <code>int<\/code>, as the operands undergo <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se9/html/jls-5.html#jls-5.6.2\" rel=\"noreferrer\">binary numeric promotion<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>c<\/code> is a <code>char<\/code><\/li>\n<li><code>1<\/code> is an <code>int<\/code><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>so <code>c<\/code> has to be widened to <code>int<\/code> to make it compatible for addition; and the result of the expression is of type <code>int<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>As for the things that \"work\":<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><code>c = (char)(c + 1)<\/code> is explicitly casting the expression to <code>char<\/code>, so its value is compatible with the variable's type;<\/li>\n<li><code>c += 1<\/code> <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se9/html/jls-15.html#jls-15.26.2\" rel=\"noreferrer\">is equivalent to<\/a> <code>c = (char) ((c) + (1))<\/code>, so it's basically the same as the previous one.<\/li>\n<li><code>c++<\/code> <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se9/html/jls-15.html#jls-15.14.2\" rel=\"noreferrer\">is of type<\/a> <code>char<\/code>, so no cast is required.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n",
            "answer_id": 53260669,
            "question_id": 53260641,
            "last_edit_date": 1542020685
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/37033a1229ea44b9f3fddd632bf0885b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 4076716,
